    <h3>Time Selection</h3>
    <p>We also know the event happened around February 2020, so we have moved the fully interactive time line at the bottom to that time domain. You can interact with the timeline by using the mousewheel when the cursor is over it, to zoom in and out the timespan. You can also click and drag the bottom area of the timeline to pan in time left and right. If you already know which days you want to investigate, you can also use the day selection widget at the right corner of the timeline.</p>
    <p>The timeline also shows points when data is available, which is also dependent on the area selection.</p>
    <p>Now that we see the availability we can click and drag on the top part of the timeline to create a time selection of interest. This will then start retrieving the data to be displayed, which will be done automatically in the next step.</p>
</section>
<section data-time="2020-01-19T00:00:00Z/2020-02-24T23:59:00Z" data-settings="S5P_OFFL_L2_NO2_PRODUCT_SUPPORT_DATA_DETAILED_RESULTS_NITROGENDIOXIDE_TOTAL_COLUMN">
    <span class="close"><i class="fa fa-times-circle"/></span>
    <h3>Data Visualization</h3>
    <p>Now the download progress is displayed. Once the download is finished, you will see buttons appear to control the model data animation.</p>
    <p>Go ahead and press the play button to see the animation!</p>
    <p>You can also change the data visualization settings for each layer by clicking the <i class="fa fa-sliders"/>-symbol of a layer.</p>
    <p>The layer settings panel has already been opened. In order to compare PANDORA station data with S5p NO2 total column measurements in the next step, we need to apply a unit conversion and multiply S5p NO2 with 2241.15. Please input x*2241.15 in the 'Data Modifier' field. In addition, we should change the maximum range to 0.5. Finally, we have to apply the changes with the 'Apply changes' button.</p>
</section>
<section data-settings="S5P_OFFL_L2_NO2_PRODUCT_SUPPORT_DATA_DETAILED_RESULTS_NITROGENDIOXIDE_TOTAL_COLUMN">
    <p>You can also see a red point of interest on the globe. These are loaded with the NO2 COLUMN_ABSORPTION SOLAR layer we previously activated.</p>
    <p>Each point represents a ground station where measured values are available. By clicking on any of them, a scatter plot will appear showing the values along the time you have selected in the timeline.</p>
    <p>When another layer is active at the same time, and data is available for the same region and time as the ground stations, the respective points will also be shown in the plot.</p>
    <p>We will select one of the stations in the next section.</p>
</section>
